How to Finance the Green Transition
New York—This week, world leaders gathered in New York at the United Nations to assess the global fight against climate change and submit new commitments to reduce emissions.
The climate crisis is of utmost importance, and our pace of action is far too slow.
We are迟迟 unable to shift into high gear.
Accelerating the pace of change requires collaborative efforts from both public and private sectors.
Luckily, thanks to the work of the Climate Finance Leadership Initiative (CFLI), private sector cooperation to combat climate change is growing increasingly prevalent.
Under the leadership of Michael Bloomberg, the UN Climate Action Envoy, CFLI was established with the mission of mobilizing private capital at the global level to address this critical issue.
This month, CFLI released a new report, "Financing the Low Carbon Future," which outlines how to expand green finance to support an orderly transition to a low-carbon economy and highlights public-private partnership opportunities to achieve the goals of the 2015 Paris Climate Agreement.
The European Investment Bank (EIB) is the largest multilateral investor in climate-related projects worldwide.
But now, in response to the call from heads of European countries and the newly elected President of the European Commission, Ursula von der Leyen, we are ready to demonstrate greater ambition and strengthen the role of the EIB as the EU's dedicated climate bank.
EIB will mainstream climate considerations, target low-carbon investments, and commit at least 1 trillion euros to low-carbon projects over the next decade.
To achieve this goal, by 2025, at least 50% of EIB financing will be directed towards climate action and environmental sustainability.
By the end of 2020, we will align all our financing activities with the goals of the Paris Climate Agreement.
As an important first step, we will exclude energy projects dependent on fossil fuels.
Furthermore, we will position EIB as a green finance incubator, committed to mobilizing other resources to help economies transition to a low-carbon future.
As an EU bank, our mission is to invest in Europe's future, and the most important issue among them is climate change.
How urgent the climate crisis is, that strong our determination is.
This summer, European countries have experienced record-high temperatures and crop failures due to last year's drought.
Many developing countries have had similar experiences.
Floods and other climate-related phenomena cost major cities billions of dollars every year, and threaten even more lives.
But the climate crisis is also an opportunity, because funding new green infrastructure can create jobs, stimulate economic growth, and reduce air pollution that plagues cities around the world.
Changing the pattern of investment can accelerate the shift away from fossil fuels. This shift has already begun.
Market forces are increasingly favoring clean energy and moving away from fossil fuels.
By 2011, more than half of the coal-fired power plants in the United States had retired, while the clean energy industry created 3.3 million jobs, compared to less than 100,000 in the coal industry.
Moreover, an increasing number of American cities and states have committed to achieving net-zero emissions by 2050.
They will receive support from the Beyond Carbon initiative, launched last year by the Bloomberg Philanthropies, aimed at supporting the full decarbonization of the US economy.
As the international community, we must not only invest in clean energy, but also reduce investments in dirty energy.
Currently, through fossil fuel subsidies, we are effectively spending money to promote climate change and air pollution.
These public funds should be used to guide investments toward electric vehicles and other technologies that can drive transformative changes in the green transition.
These investments will yield significant returns, including reducing the huge costs of air pollution on public health.
Moreover, we can take numerous measures to guide the necessary funding.
First, we must improve data and disclosure standards.
For a long time, businesses and investors had no knowledge of climate-related risks and did not understand the rationale for reducing carbon emissions or protecting assets from extreme weather events.
This is beginning to change.
The recommendations of the Task Force on Climate-related Financial Disclosures are guiding companies to allocate capital in a more sustainable way and enabling investors to reward companies that seriously address climate change.
Second, we must clarify investment risks related to green finance.
Cities contribute more than 70% of carbon dioxide emissions, but only a few cities in the developing world are able to obtain credit ratings.
As a result, total investments in clean public transport, energy-efficient buildings, and other projects that reduce emissions have been affected.
Governments and listed banks must step up efforts to help cities attract capital for these projects, including through initiatives such as the Global Covenant of Mayors for Climate & Energy, which is supported by the EIB and co-chaired by Bloomberg Philanthropies.
Third, we need to modernize the power grid.
Incentives such as refunds and tax breaks have promoted the expansion of wind and solar power, reducing costs for businesses and consumers.
Now, we should introduce similar programs to accelerate the deployment of battery storage and other emerging technologies, speeding up the overcoming of intermittency issues.
In addition, better grid connectivity can allow regions with surplus wind and solar power to supply regions with insufficient supply.
Governments can play a leading role in both areas, encouraging more private investment to flow into clean energy.
Finally, we must continue to expand the green investment market.
In 2007, the EIB issued the world's first green bond on the Luxembourg Stock Exchange, and since then, the green bond market has expanded to $136 billion.
However, compared to the global bond market of $10 trillion, this is just a drop in the ocean.
Therefore, the EIB is helping the EU develop a classification system for sustainable finance standards so that investors can compare similar projects, just as with standard bonds.
Better and more information about the carbon footprint of investments can enable investors to make informed decisions, thereby directing more private investments toward low-carbon projects.
This is how we provide financing for the green transition.
